y disassembling them to identify cost-saving opportunities.\"", "\"TEAR DOWN ANALYSIS\":\"Tear down analysis, also known as reverse engineering, involves examining a competitor's product to identify possible improvements or cost reductions.\"", "\"VALUE ENGINEERING\":\"Value engineering involves investigating the factors that affect the cost of a product or service. The aim is to improve the design of a product so the same functions can be provided for a lower cost or save cost by eliminating those the customer does not value.\"", "\"FUNCTIONAL ANALYSIS\":\"Functional analysis involves identifying the attributes/functions of a product that customers value. The price the customer is prepared to pay for each function is then determined. The function should be dropped if the cost of providing it exceeds the value it generates.\"", "\"PRODUCT LIFECYCLE\":The product lifecycle consists of stages such as development, introduction, growth, maturity, and decline. It describes how demand conditions for a product, a brand, and whole markets change over time. Different pricing policies might be adopted at various stages to maximize profits and manage demand effectively.", "\"EXAMPLE OF LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\":\"Zany developed a new computer game during the year 20X2 for $200,000. The game will be launched in the year 20X3. Budgeted revenues and costs of the game over its lifecycle are presented, showing how life-cycle costing estimates and accumulates costs over a product's entire lifecycle.\"", "\"REDESIGNING WORKFLOWS\":\"Redesigning workflows involves changing the sequence or methods of tasks to improve efficiency and reduce production costs.\"", "\"REVERSE ENGINEERING\":\"Reverse engineering, also known as tear down analysis, involves examining a competitor's product to identify possible improvements or cost reductions.\"", "\"COST REDUCTION\":\"Cost reduction involves strategies and methodologies aimed at lowering the costs associated with producing a product or delivering a service.\"", "\"PRODUCT DESIGN\":\"Product design involves creating and developing a product's form and function, often with the goal of improving usability, aesthetics, and cost-efficiency.\"", "\"BOTTLENECK IDENTIFICATION\":\"Identifying the system's bottlenecks involves determining which part of the production process limits the overall output. This is more complex in real-world scenarios compared to simplified examples.\"", "\"EXPLOITING BOTTLENECKS\":\"Deciding how to exploit the identified bottlenecks involves determining which products to make, given the bottlenecks. This requires limiting factor analysis using the time spent on the bottleneck as the limiting factor.\"", "\"SUBORDINATION TO BOTTLENECKS\":\"Subordinating everything else to the decisions made about bottlenecks ensures that other resources do not produce at a higher rate than the bottleneck. This prevents work-in-progress build-up.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}